

TERA Cybernetic Model (v3t3m9)

Overview

The TERA Cybernetic Model describes a recursive stability framework for dynamic systems evolving over time. It combines principles from cybernetics, control theory, and discrete decision logic into a unified structure that evaluates not reality itself, but the informational representation of reality.

TERA operates on the relationship between perception and model, continuously stabilizing their difference through time. It does not enforce behavior; it evaluates whether behavior remains structurally stable.


---

Core Structure

At any time , the system consists of three coupled spaces:

A(t) = \text{perception space}

B(t) = \text{model space}

C(t) = B(t) - A(t)

The objective of TERA is to regulate the evolution of , ensuring that the informational drift between perception and model remains bounded.


---

Stability Principle

Define the energy of the difference as:

V(t) = \|C(t)\|^2 = \|B(t) - A(t)\|^2

The system is considered stable if:

\Delta V(t) = V(t+1) - V(t) \le 0

This expresses a Lyapunov-type stability condition. TERA does not eliminate change; it constrains the acceleration of instability.


